erang effect"-considering a variety of rich cases that include the rise of state surveillance, the militarization of domestic law enforcement, the expanding use of drones, and torture in U.S. prisons. Synthesizing research and applying an economic lens, they develop a generalizable theory to predict and explain a startling trend. Tyranny Comes Home unveils a new aspect of the symbiotic relationship between foreign interventions and domestic politics. It gives us alarming insight into incidents like the shooting in Ferguson, Missouri and the Snowden case-which tell a common story about contemporary foreign policy and its impact on our civil liberties.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aAuthoritarianismzUnited States. 0aCivil rightszUnited States. 0aMilitarismzUnited States. 0aSocial controlzUnited States. 4aboomerang effect. 4adrones. 4aforeign intervention. 4aforeign policy. 4amilitarism. 4apolice militarization. 4asocial control. 4asurveillance. 4atorture. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Strategic Planning.2bisacsh1 aHall, Abigail R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311070368940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360528240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503605282423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503605282.jpg  a978-3-11-070368-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles